nformationExternal/NewsDisplayArticle/0,1602,5862,00.html |archive-date=2005-08-17 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> *[[Russian Navy|Russia]] ([[List of Soviet and Russian submarine classes|list]]) (some ex-[[Soviet Navy|Soviet Union]]) *[[Republic of Singapore Navy|Singapore]] *[[South African Navy|South Africa]] *[[South Korean Navy|South Korea]] *[[Spanish Navy|Spain]] ([[List of submarines in the Spanish Navy|list]])<ref>[http://reference.allrefer.com/country-guide-study/spain/spain164.html]</ref> *[[Swedish Navy|Sweden]] ([[List of submarines of the Swedish Navy|list]]) *[[Turkish Navy|Turkey]] ([[List of submarines of the Turkish Navy|list]]) *[[Royal Navy|United Kingdom]] ([[List of submarines of the Royal Navy|list]]) *[[United States Navy|United States]] ([[List of submarine classes of the United States Navy|list]]) *[[Venezuelan Navy|Venezuela]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110629103534/http://www.hazegray.org/worldnav/americas/venez.htm]</ref> *[[Vietnam People's Navy|Vietnam]]
==Ballistic Missile Submarines (SSBN)== [[File:HMS Vanguard April 1994.jpg|thumb|right|{{HMS|Vanguard|S28|6}}, a [[Royal Navy]] {{sclass-|Vanguard|submarine|0}} [[ballistic missile submarine]].]] Ballistic missile submarines are larger than any other type of submarine, in order to accommodate [[ballistic missile]]s capable of carrying [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear warheads]]. * [[People's Liberation Army Navy|China]] – [[Type 094 submarine]], [[Type 092 submarine]] * [[French Navy|France]] – {{sclass-|Triomphant|submarine|4}} * [[Russian Navy|Russia]] – {{sclass2-|Typhoon|submarine|5}}, {{sclass2-|Delta|submarine|5}}, and {{sclass2-|Borei|submarine|4}}es * [[Royal Navy|United Kingdom]] – {{sclass-|Vanguard|submarine|4}} * [[United States Navy|United States]] – {{sclass-|Ohio|submarine|4}} * [[Indian Navy|India]] – {{sclass-|Arihant|submarine|4}}
