{{Unreferenced|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
A '''spatial power combiner''' generally refers to a [[microwave]] system in which the output power of several [[Solid state (electronics)|solid state]] circuits are combined in free space as opposed to in a lossy substrate. Many spatial power combiners use concepts from free-space [[optics]] in which [[dielectric]] lenses are used to focus a microwave beam into and out of a solid-state circuit array. For this reason, this field of research is also known as [[quasioptics]].



